				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Australian Miner Arrium Rejects $1 Billion Bid by Noble Group and Posco</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Neil Gough			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2012-10-01T07:19:51+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 1, 2012 3:19 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 1, 2012 3:19 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w190 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/10/02/business/dbpix-posco/dbpix-posco-articleInline.jpg" id="100000001818244" width="190" height="190" alt="Posco, the South Korean steel maker, operates a mill in Pohang." /><span class="credit">Posco, via Reuters</span><span class="caption">Posco, the South Korean steel maker, operates a mill in Pohang.</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">HONG KONG â The Australian miner and steel maker Arrium said on Monday it had rejected a takeover offer of 1.01 billion Australian dollars ($1.05 billion) from a consortium led by the commodities trader Noble Group and the South Korean steel maker <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=PKX&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about POSCO">Posco</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In <a href="//www.asx.com.au/asxpdf/20121001/pdf/4292w1g415szg7.pdf" title="Arrium's ASX statement">a statement </a>that disclosed the unsolicited bid and announced its rejection, Arriumâs chairman, Peter Smedley, described the approach as &#8220;opportunistic,&#8221; saying the offer undervalued the company and its growth prospects. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bidding consortium â Noble, Poscoâs Australian unit, the National Pension Service of Korea, the Korea Investment Corporation and the Korea Finance Corporation â had offered 75 Australian cents a share on Friday, a 36 percent premium to the stockâs closing price that day of 55 Australian cents.  </p>

<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Australiaâs mining companies have been hard hit in recent months as prices for iron ore, coal and other important input materials have slumped because of the economic slowdown in China, Australiaâs biggest market for its natural resources. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Arrium employs 11,000 people. It manufactures and recycles steel while also mining iron ore at its Middleback Ranges site in South Australia. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares in the firm soared 25 percent on Monday on news of the takeover bid, closing at 68 Australian cents, but that was still only half of what they traded at as recently as May. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In response to Arriumâs announcement on Monday, the Noble Group, which led the bidding consortium, <a href="//info.sgx.com/webcoranncatth.nsf/VwAttachments/Att_90B12096029A411048257A8A00017930/$file/Announcement_011012.pdf?openelement" title="Noble Group's SGX announcement">made an announcement</a> to the stock exchange in Singapore, where it is listed, suggesting that the matter was far from concluded. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;At this stage, the expression of interest from the consortium is nonbinding and incomplete, and the transaction may, depending on how it is finally structured, be subject to conditions, including but not limited to, satisfactory arrangements with lenders with respect to Arriumâs debt profile on a change of control,&#8221; Nobleâs announcement said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Arrium, based in Sydney, is being advised by UBS and the law firm Allens Linklaters. </p>
	</div>
